We add -1/2 times the first equation to the second to find \begin{aligned} 2x &+ &2y &= &5 \\ & &-5y &= &-5/2 , \end{aligned}
which shows that y=1/2 and x=2 is the unique solution.
Gaussian elimination says that we should add the first and second equations: \begin{aligned} -x &+ &y &= &1 \\ & &2y &= &3 \end{aligned}
giving y=3/2 and x=1/2 as the only solution.
Row reduction (specifically, subtracting the first equation from the second) \begin{aligned} x &- &3y &+ &z &= &1 \\ & &4y &+ &z &= &13 \end{aligned}
shows, because the variable z does not have a pivot in the corresponding column, and hence is a free variable, that there are many solutions.
Row reduction (subtracting 3 times the first equation from the second) \begin{aligned} -x &- &y &= &1 \\ & &0 &= &-1 \end{aligned}
shows that there is no solution.
Interchanging the first and fourth equations gives \begin{aligned} x &+ &y &- &z &= &10 \\ 2x &- &2y &+ &z &= &0 \\ x & & &+ &z &= &5 \\ & &4y &+ &z &= &20. \end{aligned}
Now subtracting the first equation from the third and adding -2 times the first equation to the second equation yields \begin{aligned}
x &+ &y &- &z &= &10 \\ & &-4y &+ &3z &= &-20\\ & &-y &+ &2z &= &-5 \\ & &4y &+ &z &= &20 . \end{aligned}
Finally, we add the second and fourth equations and subtract 1/4 times the second row from the third row to obtain \begin{aligned} x &+ &y &- &z &= &10 \\ & &-4y &+ &3z &= &-20\\ & & & &(5/4)z &= &0 \\ & & & &4z &= &0, \end{aligned}
which gives the unique solution (x,y,z)=(5,5,0) .
We begin by subtracting twice the first equation from the fourth equation and adding -3/2 times the first equation to the third equation to obtain the system \begin{aligned}
2x & & &+ &z &+ &w &= &5 \\ & &y & & &- &w &= &-1 \\ & & &- &(5/2)z &- &(5/2)w &= &-15/2 \\ & &y & & &- &w &= &-1. \end{aligned}
Subtracting the second equation from the fourth gives us the system \begin{aligned}
2x & & &+ &z &+ &w &= &5 \\ & &y & & &- &w &= &-1 \\ & & &- &(5/2)z &- &(5/2)w &= &-15/2 \\ & & & & & &0 &= &0, \end{aligned}
which shows that there are many solutions.
